    <p>LON­DON • A doc­tor look­ing into pos­si­ble links be­tween foot­ball and de­men­tia has said Eng­land’s 1966 World Cup-win­ning mid­fielder Nobby Stiles, who died aged 78 in Oc­to­ber, suf­fered se­vere brain dam­age from re­peat­edly head­ing the ball.</p>
    <p>Stiles had been di­ag­nosed with de­men­tia, as were sev­eral of his team­mates in­clud­ing Jack and Bobby Charl­ton. Fol­low­ing a study, neu­ropathol­o­gist Wil­lie Stewart told his fam­ily it was the re­sult of head­ing the ball over the sus­tained pe­riod of his ca­reer.</p>


